<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}+{3}{y}=-{27}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{6}{x}+{2}{y}={52}</m></p>
<p><input type="text" style="width:10.6ch" name="qn0" id="qn0" value="" autocomplete="off" aria-label="Question 1" class="text"/></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left({7},{5}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of -6. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle-\frac{{6}}{{-{{6}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{{6}}}{{-{{6}}}}{\left(-{6}{x}+{3}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{{6}}}{{-{{6}}}}{\left(-{27}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left({6}\right)}{x}+{3}{y}=-{27}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{6}{x}+{2}{y}={52}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{5}{y}={25}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=\frac{{25}}{{5}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={5}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}+{3}{\left({5}\right)}=-{27}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}+{\left({15}\right)}=-{27}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}=-{27}-{\left({15}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{6}{x}=-{42}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-\frac{{42}}{{-{{6}}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}={7}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left({7},{5}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>